        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(signal): guard containerRestRequest JSON.parse against malformed responses",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n**What problem does this PR solve?**\n\n- Fix classification: Defensive `JSON.parse` crash-protection in `containerRestRequest`, the single REST entry point for the bbernhard Signal container.\n- Root cause: `containerRestRequest:262` calls `JSON.parse(text)` without try/catch. `readProviderTextResponse` already bounds the body (16 MiB shared provider cap), but a malformed JSON body within that cap still throws unhandled `SyntaxError`.\n- Why this is root-cause fix: Wraps the single `JSON.parse` site with try/catch, matching the existing error-path patterns already present in the same function (line 250: `.catch(() => \"\")` on error body read).\n- Patch quality notes: 2 files, +6/-2 lines. The test (\"handles JSON parse errors gracefully\") was already present — this PR tightens the assertion to the specific error message `\"Signal REST returned malformed JSON\"`.\n\n**Why does this matter now?**\n\n- User impact: A malformed response from the Signal REST container currently throws raw `SyntaxError` with no actionable context.\n\n**What is the intended outcome?**\n\n- The `containerRestRequest` function throws `Error(\"Signal REST returned malformed JSON\")` instead of `SyntaxError`, matching the error-path handling convention already in the function.\n\n**What is intentionally out of scope?**\n\n- Does NOT change: error-body path (already bounded+catch), empty-body path (returns undefined), attachment download path, WebSocket receive path, or the `readProviderTextResponse` size cap.\n\n**What should reviewers focus on?**\n\n- Architecture check: `readProviderTextResponse` at line 257 already bounds the body; this PR only adds parse-error wrapping in the guarded path — no new dependencies or boundary changes.",
